04523nam a22006975i 9780824862619DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20002000hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248626197 a10.1515/97808248626192doi  a(DE-B1597)483726  a(OCoLC)1024019957  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aHQ1762.R68 2001eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aRosenberger, Nancy R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGambling With Virtue :bJapanese Women and the Search for Self in a Changing Nation /cNancy R. Rosenberger. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I :Glimpses into the ’70s: Reworking -- tChapter 1. Institutional Selves: Women Teachers -- tChapter 2. Virtuous Selves: Housewives -- tPART II :Glimpses into the ’80s -- tChapter 3 .Backstage Selves: Housewives -- tChapter 4. Fulfilled Selves? Working Women -- tPART III: Glimpses into the ’90s -- tChapter 5. Centrifugal Selves: Housewives -- tChapter 6. Compassionate Selves: Women and Elder Care -- tChapter 7. Selves Centered on Self: Young Single Women -- tChapter 8. No Self, True Self, or Multiple Selves? -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGambling with Virtue rings with the voices of women speaking openly about their struggle to be both modern and Japanese in the late twentieth century. It brings to the fore the complexity of women's everyday lives as they navigate through home, work, and community. Meanwhile, women fashion selves that acknowledge and challenge the social order. Nancy Rosenberger gives us their voices and experiences interspersed with introductions to public ideas of the last three decades that contribute significantly to the opportunities and risks women encounter in their journeys. Rosenberger uses the stage as a metaphor to demonstrate how everyday life requires Japanese women to be skilled performers. She shows how they function on stage in their accepted roles while effecting small but significant changes backstage. Over the last thirty years, Japanese women have expanded their influence and extended this cultural process of multiple arenas to find compromises between the old virtues of personhood and new ideals for self. They conform, maneuver, and make choices within these multiple stages as they juggle various concerns and desires. By the 1990s their personal choices have made a difference, calling into question the very nature of these multiple arenas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aSelf-perception in womenzJapan. 0aWomenzJapan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486261940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824862619423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824862619.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK